Hypervisor is the controller of our virtual machine and virtual network
Type 1 hypervisor: hypervisor connected to the hardware, bare metal
Type 2 hypervisor: software defined

Use Hyper-V
From "Features on or off" select Hyper-V and restart

We create an Ubuntu server on VirtualBox


QEMU
sudo apt install qemu-kvm libvirt-daemon bridge-utils virt-manager

Post-installation, add your current user to the libvirt and kvm groups:
sudo usermod -aG libvirt $(whoami)
sudo usermod -aG kvm $(whoami)

sudo systemctl start libvirtd
sudo systemctl enable libvirtd

mkdir Ubuntu-VM
sudo mv /path/to/ubuntu.iso ./Ubuntu-VM
qemu-img create -f qcow2 Image.img 20G
qemu-system-x86_64 -enable-kvm -cdrom ubuntu.iso -boot menu=on -drive file=Image.img -m 4G -cpu host -vga virtio -display sdl,gl=on

Usint virt manager we may need to configure the network interface for it to autostart when powering up the vm
$sudo virsh net-list --all
$sudo virsh net-autostart <name of the interface>

Launch machine without using virt-manager
$sudo virsh start <machine_name>
$sudo virsh domstate <machine_name> //check state of the vm
$sudo virsh shutdown <machine_name>

 
